<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-104-874  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 104 874.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  March 14 1989 v3 n11 p6(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>House considers tougher laws to combat computer viruses. (House ofRepresentatives)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brower, Emily.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer VirusesComputer CrimesLegal IssuesLegislationUnited States. Congress. House.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>House considers tougher laws to combat computer virusesandM;Washington -- Heightened public awareness of computer viruses and theirintrusion into Capitol Hill computers has prompted a group of U.S.andO;congressmen to propose an amendment that would make virus programming afederal crime.andM;Originally sponsored by Rep.andP;  Paul Herger, R-Calif., the Computer VirusEradication Act of 1989, or H.R.andP;  55, would amend the Computer Fraud andAbuse Act of 1986 with a new section covering computer viruses.andM;Now under consideration by the House Judiciary Committee, H.R.andP;  55 would makethe creation and insertion of &quot;information or commands&quot; that may cause &quot;loss,expense  or risk to health or welfare,&quot; punishable under civil and criminalcodes.andM;The bill is worded to cover infections incurred by the spread of a virus fromone computer to another and entitles individuals to relief from virusdamages.andM;&quot;This bill is aimed at the classic case of someone writing a virus withcriminal intent,&quot; said Rep.andP;  Robert Carr, D-Mich., the primary co-sponsor ofthe bill.andM;&quot;The role of computers is becoming so pervasive and the damage of viruses canbe so insidious, it relates to the very integrity of our society,&quot; he said.andM;But Carr said he would like to see the Computer Virus Eradication Act madetougher on virus programmers.andP;  &quot;In my judgment, H.R.andP;  55 has insufficientdetergents for virus programmers,&quot; he said.andM;Lawyers agreed that the law could be improved by adding more detail to theamendment.andP;  &quot;Some other more extensive liability should be included, such asa minimum statutory damages payable to the aggrieved party,&quot; said Jack Russo,an attorney with Nelson and Russo of Palo Alto, Calif.andM;Carr predicted that the bill will pass once these improvements are added.andO;H.R.andP;  55 is the only law that &quot;hits the nail on the head&quot; for prosecutingvirus programmers, he said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>